{{use mdy dates|date=January 2016}} '''David E. Blackmer''' (January 11, 1927 – March 21, 2002) was an American audio electronics engineer, most famous as the inventor of the [[DBX (noise reduction)|DBX noise reduction system]] and founder of [[dbx (company)|dbx]].<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Hoffman | first1 = F. | title = Encyclopedia of Recorded Sound, Volume 1 | publisher = Taylor & Francis | edition = revised | year = 2004 }}</ref>
As well as [[audio noise reduction]], Blackmer worked on extending the frequency response of audio electronics beyond the conventionally accepted audible range of 20&nbsp;kHz. He also published research on the value of ultrasonic frequencies in sound reproduction, claiming that the time resolution of human hearing is 5 microseconds or better—which would correspond to a frequency of 200&nbsp;kHz, requiring audio equipment ideally to have a flat response to that frequency.<ref name="Beyond 20 kHz">{{cite web|last1=Blackmer|first1=David|title=The World Beyond 20&nbsp;kHz|url=http://www.earthworksaudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/The-world-beyond-20kHz.pdf|website=Earthworks Audio|accessdate=1 June 2014|format=pdf|date=1999}}</ref>
Blackmer attended [[High Mowing School]] in [[Wilton, New Hampshire]]. He started in audio at [[Lafayette Radio]] in [[Boston]] in the 1940s and studied [[electronics]] in the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] and at [[Harvard University]] and [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]. He later worked at [[Trans-Radio Recording Studio]], [[Epsco]], [[Hi-Con Eastern]] and [[Raytheon Corporation|Raytheon]], where he designed [[telemetry]] systems for the [[mercury program|Mercury space program]]. He founded dbx in 1971, selling it to [[Birmingham Sound Reproducers|BSR]] in 1979 and staying on with the company for several years. In the late 1980s he formed [[Earthworks (corporation)|Earthworks]], producing studio [[microphone]]s, [[preamplifier]]s and studio reference [[Loudspeaker|monitors]]. He also founded [[Kintek]] (now [[Colortek]]) and [[Charles Stark Draper Laboratory|Instrumentation Laboratory]]{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}, as well as running the [[Cafe Pierrot]] restaurant in Wilton for a time.
Blackmer was a life member of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] and a fellow of the [[Audio Engineering Society]] from 1976. He was also a great reader of [[science fiction]]. He had ten children.
== A partial list of patents held by David Blackmer ==
* {{US patent|3681618}}, August 1, 1972: RMS Circuits with Bipolar Logarithmic Converter * {{US patent|3714462}}, January 30, 1973: Multiplier Circuits * {{US patent|4403199}}, September 6, 1983: Gain control systems * {{US patent|6091829}}, July 18, 2000: Microphone apparatus * {{US patent|6526149}}, February 25, 2003: System and method for reducing non linear electrical distortion in an electroacoustic device
